<h1>Looking at the Data... How Green are these States?</h1>

<div class="well">
  <p>
  The null hypothesis is that the two averages are similar (data is within 95% normal distribution). If the null hypothesis is rejected, this means the two samples are statistically different. One big assumption to be made with t-tests are that the variances are equal (roughly equated to standard deviations), so the p value for both equal variance scenarios is included.
</p>
<p>
  The t-test equation:
